newal projects, managed to carve out a geographic and racial place in one of America’s great cities. Through their experiences in the city’s central neighborhoods over the course of these three decades, Fernández demonstrates how Mexicans and Puerto Ricans collectively articulated a distinct racial position in Chicago, one that was flexible and fluid, neither black nor white.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aHispanic American neighborhoodszIllinoiszChicagoxHistoryy20th century. 0aMexican AmericanszIllinoiszChicagoxHistoryy20th century. 0aMexicanszIllinoiszChicagoxHistoryy20th century. 0aNear West Side (Chicago, Ill.) - History - 20th century. 0aPuerto RicanszIllinoiszChicagoxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  achicago, mexicans, puerto rican, assimilation, race, ethnicity, immigration, racism, west side, pilsen, mujeres latinas en accion, young lords, gangs, 20th century, illinois, history, nonfiction, politics, sociology, discrimination, labor, housing, class, settlements, urban renewal, activism, la dieciocho, neighborhoods, chicano movement, pride, nationalism, gender, displacement, color line, integration, community.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG and UP eBook Package 2000-2015z978311063872108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z97831106353860 cprintz978022624425940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226244280423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226244280/original  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-063872-1  DG and UP eBook Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles